==Things to do to Conserve Energy in the House==
A great guide for conserving energy at home is the [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/ EERE website].

All of the following ideas will not only conserve energy but also save you money over the life cycle of the product. Some ideas such as temperature set backs will save money with no investment - others such as [[CFL]]s will cost a modest amount of money up front (e.g. $5) but will save you a considerable amount over the life cycle (e.g. >$30 for CFLs).

*[[House insulation]] (including floors over unheated spaces)
*Caulk [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/insulation_airsealing/index.cfm/mytopic=11270] and weather-strip [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/insulation_airsealing/index.cfm/mytopic=11280] around all openings and cracks
*'''Water heaters''': Turn down water heater temperature -- Set water-heater thermostat at 120 F [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/water_heating/index.cfm/mytopic=13090]; Insulate hot water pipes [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/water_heating/index.cfm/mytopic=13060]; insulate water-heating unit [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/water_heating/index.cfm/mytopic=13070] ; install heat traps on water heater [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/water_heating/index.cfm/mytopic=13100]
*Add storm windows and doors (consider using plastic) [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/windows_doors_skylights/index.cfm/mytopic=13490]
*Install insulated shades, panels, or draperies on all windows - [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/windows_doors_skylights/index.cfm/mytopic=13500 window treatments]
*Ventilate attic and crawl space
*Conduct general repairs to reduce air infiltration
* '''Furnace''': Tune-up furnace and water heater annually; Insulate furnace ducts and heat supply lines; Install clock thermostat on furnace (turn down furnace when not needed - set back at night and when away)
*Replace shower heads with water-saving type
*Build a vestibule around exterior doors
*'''Lighting''': Replace incandescent lighting with fluorescent lights such as [[CFL]]s or [[LED]]s; Consider task lighting
*Redesign landscaping; add foliage to block or divert winds 
*Paint interior walls with light, warm colors
*Provide exterior air sources for furnace and/or fireplace
*Install glass doors on fireplace or install air-tight stove in fireplace opening

==Energy Star==
When you purchase any product that uses [[energy]] - from large purchases like refrigerators to less expensive purchases like telephones - consider purchasing the [http://www.energystar.gov/index.cfm?fuseaction=find_a_product. Energy star] product. Products in more than 50 categories are eligible for the ENERGY STAR. They use less energy, save money, and help protect the environment. '''When shopping -- Ask for the ENERGY STAR.'''
*Install energy-saving appliances such as those that are rated [http://www.energystar.gov/ Energy Star] also see: [http://www.eere.energy.gov/consumer/your_home/appliances/index.cfm/mytopic=10020 Consumer's guide to energy efficiency appliances]

==Renewable Energy==
*Install [[renewable energy]] sources such as [[wind power]] or [[solar]]: both [[solar hot water]] heaters and [[photovoltaic]] panels

